80 million uninsured means that about 250 Million people have insurance and are well taken care of. Instead of trying to change the ENTIRE medical structure to benefit the ones that don't have it, why not instead focus on something MUCH easier, helping those people learn skills which they can use to get a high paying job that offers insurance. Because in reality, if you're making it in America but can't afford insurance, a policy which is about $500-$600 per month can cover your ENTIRE FAMILY. Help people make an extra $6000-$7000 per year, and there is all your insurance coverage.
Also - Read your freaking coverage plan, don't just get insurance and think "Ok I'm good"...Read it, and you won't have any surprises. And if it's denied, you'll know for sure if it's covered or not without needing a lawyer. Because you read the damn thing

snippet.textDisplay:
American Healthcare is extremely expensive: It's also extremely effective. Look up the death rates of terminal illnesses. It's roughly 30-50% lower than the U.K. mainly due to the U.K. having extreme wait times for procedures and outdated equipment(which is made in the U.S., alongside 99% of the worlds vaccines.)
The reason everything is so expensive is because our healthcare system has legislation preventing it from being sold in the open market, for example, I can't choose where to get my X-Rays, and if I do get an X-Ray, it's illegal for my doctor to look at it, and use it to give me a medical opinion. Which leads to medical facilities jacking up prices because they know insurance companies are paying for it, not the individual. And this leads to people without that insurance being screwed when it comes time to see a doctor.
My best advice for anyone in America, get health insurance at a young age while it's cheap, because when you get older and start having health problems, you'll regret not getting it sooner.

snippet.textDisplay:
I love that GoFundMe actually allows capitalism to function. As America's medical system has grown increasingly regulated and Socialized over the decades the costs of care have done nothing but skyrocket. This will of course only get worse if so-called universal health insurance is implemented. You think $100,000 is expensive wait until you're paying a thousand dollars a month in taxes to fund state managed health insurance. Do the quick math there. That is $120,000 every ten years and over a million over the course of your lifetime. Real cheap, and that is for everyone, not only those who actually suffer serious medical problems.

Thankfully there is an outlet as of yet uncontrolled by the State that allows people to privately and voluntarily help each other to the best of their abilities without the violent interference, gross mismanagement, and nightmarish bureaucracy of the government.

snippet.textDisplay: Ok. Last time for all the gullible Americans who think people die waiting for treatment in Canadian ERs .... it doesn't happen. I took my mom to the ER last month because we thought she might be having a stroke. She was taken back right away and we were in and out in less than 3 hours. She had a CT scan and blood tests and god knows what else. Fortunately she wasn't having a stroke. And it cost us nothing. When she called me I just about lost my mind but I didn't hesitate to get it checked out. I can only imagine how terrifying it must be to wonder if a loved one is dying and not be able to get that piece of mind without worrying about going bankrupt. How would I have felt if we were in America and I said gee mom, I can't afford to take you to the hospital so hopefully it's not a stroke but hey if it is can you make it a killer because I can't afford to care for you if you're just permanently disabled from a stroke we didn't treat quick enough. In America how many people end up seriously injured because they wait because they know they can't afford treatment. Seconds count. Ffs America wake up!
